<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="359" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="359">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kanmiya, 1971" authorityName="Kanmiya" authorityYear="1971" box="[779,1132,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidiventris">
<emphasis box="[779,948,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="359">D. nitidiventris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kanmiya, K." box="[956,1132,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="359" pagination="157 - 180" refId="ref12133" refString="Kanmiya, K. (1971) Study on the genus Dicraeus Loew from Japan and Formosa (Diptera, Chloropidae). Mushi, 45, 157 - 180." type="journal article" year="1971">Kanmiya, 1971</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated from the latter by the following features: all femora black with both ends yellow; abdomen brown except for tergite 1 yellow; cercus long, 0.4 times as long as surstylus, with a small odontoid process distally. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kanmiya" authorityYear="1971" box="[1201,1371,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidiventris">
<emphasis box="[1201,1371,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="359">D. nitidiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, only the fore femur is black; the abdomen is entirely black; and the cercus is small and vestigial (
<bibRefCitation author="Kanmiya, K." box="[1181,1352,692,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="359" pagination="157 - 180" refId="ref12133" refString="Kanmiya, K. (1971) Study on the genus Dicraeus Loew from Japan and Formosa (Diptera, Chloropidae). Mushi, 45, 157 - 180." type="journal article" year="1971">Kanmiya 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[151,1324,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="359" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,752]" box="[151,1324,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="359">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is from the Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Yang &amp; Nartshuk" authorityYear="2019" box="[699,794,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentatus">
<emphasis box="[699,794,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="359">dentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(“dentiform”), referring to the shape of cercus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
